    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Pointed Questions About the Ultimate Penalty</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jim McMullen letter says reasoning in June 23 editorial condemning execution in Texas undermines reasoning in numerous editorials supporting a woman's right to abortion</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your June 23 editorial ''Irreversible Error in Texas'' rightly proclaims that ''there can be no margin for error when the state takes human life.'' Of all the myriad reasons for eliminating the death penalty, the most compelling is that an innocent man could be condemned. Your argument, though, proves to be too much.</p>
        <p>You consistently and forcefully defend the right of a woman to have an abortion free of state interference.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your June 23 editorial ''Irreversible Error in Texas'' rightly proclaims that ''there can be no margin for error when the state takes human life.'' Of all the myriad reasons for eliminating the death penalty, the most compelling is that an innocent man could be condemned. Your argument, though, proves to be too much.</p>
        <p>You consistently and forcefully defend the right of a woman to have an abortion free of state interference.</p>
        <p>Will you not recognize even the possibility that an unborn child may also be an innocent human life worthy of state protection?</p>
        <p>JIM MC MULLEN  Dallas, June 23, 2000</p>
      </block>
